article.description:
Jamal Mashburn scored 27 points, including a
key jumper with 32.1 seconds remaining, as the New Orleans Hornets
beat the Philadelphia 76ers 94-89 on Sunday night.
article.headline: 76ers fail to clinch home-court advantage in first round
article.linkText: Mashburn, Hornets pull away from 76ers down stretch
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The New Orleans Hornets played like a different team in the second half.
Mashburn

Jamal Mashburn scored 27 points, including a key jumper with 32.1 seconds remaining, as the Hornets used a strong second half to beat the Philadelphia 76ers 94-89 on Sunday night. "A lot of people stepped up today,'' Mashburn said. "In the first half, we didn't move the ball very well, but we changed all that in the second half. We just played basketball. That's what it came down to.'' The Sixers led 78-71 with 7:12 to play, but Stacey Augmon scored six straight points as the Hornets went on an 11-2 run to take their first lead of the game, 82-80. "We lost our poise in the first three minutes of the second half,'' 76ers coach Larry Brown said. "And I think that's happened to us before.'' Baron Davis scored 16 points in his first game back after missing three with a sore left knee, and Jamaal Magloire had 14 points and 10 rebounds for New Orleans. Allen Iverson scored 30 points, including 22 in the first half for the Sixers -- who missed an opportunity to clinch home-court advantage in the first round of the playoffs. Iverson shot just 2-for-11 from the floor, and was guarded by Augmon. "I thought that Stacey did a great job in the second half,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas said. "We put him in the game and he just ball-hawked him all over the court. When A.I.'s hitting and everything is going smoothly, everybody else picks up on it. When he's not, then they have to depend on others to come home.'' Philadelphia's loss, coupled with the second-place Detroit Pistons' win Sunday means the Sixers can finish no higher than third in the NBA's Eastern Conference. As of now, the Sixers will meet the Boston Celtics in the first round, but there is still a chance they will face the Hornets. "I'm not going to worry about that now,'' Brown said. "I don't know who we'll have. But if we've got (New Orleans), it'll be tough.'' Philadelphia tied it on an 18-footer from Eric Snow, but Davis answered with a 3-pointer to put the Hornets up by three. After Mashburn's jumper gave the Hornets an 89-84 lead, Eric Snow made a 3-pointer with 20 seconds remaining. Snow also had a 3-point attempt to tie it with under 5 seconds left, but the shot fell short of the rim. Davis was held scoreless in 11 first-quarter minutes before heading to the bench to ice his knee. He did not record his first field goal until 7:52 of the second quarter. "I might be 80 percent, but I'm probably closer to 70 percent,'' he said. "I'm just trying to play through it.'' The Sixers opened with a 9-2 run and held the lead for the entire first half. Iverson hit nine of 10 first-half free throws and a 3-pointer with 3.6 seconds left in the second quarter to put the Sixers up 53-41 at the half. Game notes
Sunday's game was the first since Jan. 24th that the Hornets' original starting lineup of P.J. Brown, Davis, Mashburn, Magloire and David Wesley played together. They were 21-14 since. ... The Sixers played their fifth straight without starting F Keith Van Horn (left plantar fascia strain), and C Derrick Coleman (strained left thigh/bruised left hip) missed his second straight. Both players did not dress. ... Duncan Taylor, the Deputy Consul-General of the British Embassy, received a standing ovation from the First Union Center crowd when he was introduced at the end of the first quarter.
